      "`x : C`, so `⊤ c = ⊤`, and thus we get `⨆ p in D.carrier, p c = ⊤`, as desired.\n\n   Therefore, we can write:\n   - `(sSup D.carrier) c = ⨆ p in D.carrier, p c` (by definition of `sSup` in `PersistenceSubmodule`)\n   - `sSup D.carrier = ⊤` (by `D.sSup_eq_top'`)\n   - So `(sSup D.carrier) c = ⊤ c = ⊤`.\n   - Hence, `⨆ p in D.carrier, p c = ⊤`.\n\n   But in Lean, we have the goal `⨆ p, ↑p c = ⊤`. This is `⨆ (p : I), (p : PersistenceSubmodule M) c = ⊤`, where `I` is coerced to `{p : PersistenceSubmodule M // p ∈ D.carrier}`. But this is the same as `⨆ (p in D.carrier), p c`, because the supremum over the subtype is the same as over the set. Therefore, we can use the above reasoning.\n\n3. **Formal Proof Sketch**:\n   - We have `sSup D.carrier = ⊤` (from `D.sSup_eq_top'`).\n   - The supremum of a set of `PersistenceSubmodule` is pointwise, so `(sSup D.carrier) c = ⨆ p in D.carrier, p c`.\n   - But `(sSup D.carrier) c = ⊤ c = ⊤` because `sSup D.carrier = ⊤`.\n   - Therefore, `⨆ p in D.carrier, p c = ⊤`.\n   - Now, `⨆ p, ↑p c = ⨆ p in D.carrier, p c` because the supremum over the subtype `I` (the carrier set of `D`) is the same as over the set (they are definitionally equal?).\n   - Therefore, `⨆ p, ↑p c = ⊤`.\n\n   However, in Lean, `⨆ p : I, ↑p c` is actually `⨆ (p : {p : PersistenceSubmodule M // p ∈ D.carrier}), p.val c`, which is the same as `⨆ (p in D.carrier), p c` because `{p : X // p ∈ S}` is equivalent to `S` as a set. The supremum over the subtype is the same as over the set.\n\n   So perhaps we can use the fact that `iSup_subtype` is equal to `iSup` over the set.\n\n   Alternatively, perhaps it is better to note that `⨆ p : I, ↑p c` is by definition `⨆ (p : {p : PersistenceSubmodule M // p ∈ D.carrier}), p.val c`, and then we can prove that this is equal to `⨆ (p in D.carrier), p c`, using a lemma about the supremum over a subtype.\n\n   But perhaps in Lean, the coercion from `I` to `PersistenceSubmodule M` is `fun p : I ↦ p.val`, so `⨆ p : I, p.val c 